Predicting Yelp! Ratings

Goal

This project aims to predict the number of stars a Yelp! user has given a business, using the words used in the review as well as the data about the user that Yelp saves. This will be done using random forests.

Data Source

The data was sourced from www.yelp.com/dataset/

The files can be downloaded directly to the computer in JSON format. The R code to convert the files to an R dataframe is included in the data processing section.

Data Processing

Wrangling the review data

																										#name of file
review_file = "yelp_academic_dataset_review.json"

#import review data and convert to dataframe
review_data = jsonlite::stream_in(
  textConnection(readLines(review_file, n=10000)), verbose=F)

The original JSON file is close to 7GB. This cannot be processed by my laptop. In order to combat this, I only read in a subset of the data. In only reading 10 thousand lines, we have plenty of data to analyse, but the size of the dataframe is small enough that the time and RAM it uses is reasonable.

The conversion from JSON to a dataframe was not a problem, as I had predicted it might be. There is a library (jsonlite) in R that makes these files very easy to handle. The stream_in function automatically changes the format for us.

The review data was already very clean - it had one row per observation and one column per variable. The tidying can be seen in appendix 1. The only steps I had to carry out are:

  • I used the mutate function to combine all the categories of votes into one column. This is so we can better see a relationship between the amount of positive reaction towards the review and the star rating. Since all the categories are positive (and very similar) reactions, it makes sense to group them into one variable (***)

  • I removed the unwanted columns such as the date/time the review was made, as well as the ID of the review that yelp gives it.

The column names before and after the tidying are below:

																											colnames(review_data)

Wrangling the user data

																										#name of file
user_file = "yelp_academic_dataset_user.json"

#import user data and convert to dataframe
user_data = jsonlite::stream_in(
  textConnection(readLines(user_file, n=10000000)), verbose=F)
user_data = user_data %>% filter(user_id %in% review_data$user_id)

This step took a long time - I had to outsource running this code to another (more powerful) computer to import and tidy the data since the file is so big. Once it had run once, I saved the file as a csv. This meant I didnt have to go through the processing again every time I worked on the project. I read in the csv file with the read.csv() command.

An issue that I had at the beginning was that I wasnt sure which files to use. This wasnt a problem in the end; as the goal of the project was refined, we realized that the other files (check-in data, business data and tip data) were not relevant to the direction of the project and therefore we dont have to worry about them.

The user data tidying can be found in appendix 2.

The changes I made are:

  • Changing the elite_status variable into a yes/no variable. We are not interested in when the user was elite, especially because the review and user data covers years from 2009 all the way up to 2019.
  • Combining all the categories for votes into one numerical variable for the total votes sent. Also combining all the categories for compliments received into one numeric variable for the total number of compliments received. This is for the same reasons as the line marked with (***) above.
  • Creating a categorical variable for the year the user joined yelp.
  • Adding the prefix user_ to all the columns in order to differentiate the user data from the review data
  • I made sure to remove the average stars given by a user since this is very much dependent on the number of stars the user gives any particular review (the very value our model is trying to estimate). I did not want this to be a predictor variable for the model.

Wrangling the combined file

The code for this can be seen in appendix 3.

First, I combined the user and review dataframes into one called no_freq_data.

Next, using the tidytext and textdata packages, I took a list of all the words that have either a positive or negative connotation. I made each word a new column name. For each review, the number in that column refers to how many times that word was written in said review.

I save this dataset as freq_data to reflect the fact that this has columns for the frequency of words (as opposed to no_freq_data which does not). Now, it is worth noting that no_freq_data has 1,000,000 rows, whereas I was only able to get 10,000 rows for freq_data. This is due to RAM limitations. I will discuss the pros and cons of using each dataset later on.

Data Exploration

What is the distribution of the number of stars?

																										ggplot(data = no_freq_data, aes(x=stars))+
  theme_minimal() +
  geom_histogram(aes(y=..count../sum(..count..)), bins=5, fill="lightblue", color = "white", ) +
  geom_vline(xintercept=mean(review_data_tidy$stars), colour="red") +
  geom_vline(xintercept=median(review_data_tidy$stars), colour="blue")

Here, using ggplot, I am plotting the frequency of the number of stars given. The red line shows the mean (at around 3.73), and the blue line shows the median (at 4).

We can see that almost half the reviews give the business 5 stars. Only about 1 in 5 reviews gave either a 2 or a 3 star rating. It seems like, the higher the number of stars, the more reviews. This excludes the 1 star rating which has a higher number of reviews than wed expect. This does make sense intuitively, as someone will more likely leave a review if they have a particularly high or low opinion of the business.

Knowing the distribution of stars is not uniform is relevant to our data analysis; we want the model to predict the number of stars according to this distribution (not a uniform one).

I did the same analysis but this time for the negative words. Here, the top three words (small, wait and bad) have much higher frequency than the rest.

This analysis tells us that using the tidytext classification of positive and negative words might be inaccurate, as it is not designed specifically for the data we are interested in. Some notable examples are:

  • waffle, yelp and cheap are all negative words according to the dictionary that we are using. However, in context, these are all positive, or neutral words.
  • soup, lamb and other food-related nouns are all labeled as positive, but in this context, they are most likely neutral as they dont give any value judgement

It would be interesting to include this sort of sentiment analysis in our final model.

Do the number of stars depend on how many reviews a user has made?

																											ggplot(data = head(no_freq_data,1000), aes(y=log(user_review_count), x=factor(stars), colour=factor(stars)))+
  theme_minimal() + 
  geom_point() + 
  geom_jitter()
																										

																											ggplot(data = head(no_freq_data,1000), aes(y=log(user_review_count),x = factor(stars), fill=factor(stars))) +
  theme_minimal() + 
  geom_boxplot()

I first used a scatter plot with jitter to plot the number of stars given against the log of the number of reviews left by a user. Since its quite hard to read, I also plotted a box and whisker plot.

We can see that there does seem to be some correlation between the review count and the number of stars. Whether this is significant or not is of course yet to be analyzed but the plots do indicate it is worth including in the data analysis later. The heights of the upper and lower quartiles and medians do seem change as the number of stars changes.

It appears that for any number of stars up to 4, the more stars given, the more reviews a user is likely to have given. For the five star case, however, the expected number of reviews is lower than the number expected for 2,3 or 4 stars.

Its hard to say why this might be. Perhaps first time users are more likely to give an extreme rating, while long-time users are more nuanced.

Its interesting to see that the shape of the box plots is very similar over the different star ratings.

It looks as if the user_review_count will be a useful explanatory variable in the model.

I first wanted to alter the no_freq_data dataframe to include the count of positive and negative words as explanatory variables:

																											testpos <- unnested_data %>%
  semi_join(positive_words) %>%
  group_by(review_id) %>%
  summarize(positivewords=n())

testneg <- unnested_data %>%
  semi_join(negative) %>%
  group_by(review_id) %>%
  summarize(negativewords=n())

no_freq_data <- no_freq_data %>%
  left_join(testpos, by="review_id") %>%
  left_join(testneg, by="review_id")

Note that now we have two dataframes:

  • freq_data has columns for the user data and for the frequencies of words. This has 10,000 rows

  • no_freq_data has columns for the user dara and for the count of positive/negative words as classified by the tidytext package. This has 1,000,000 rows.

Weighing up the positives and negatives of both, we have:

freq_data

  • Many more columns - takes longer to run

  • More complicated model - Occams razor

  • The variables appear to explain variation in the data

  • Fewer datapoints available

no_freq_data

  • Fewer columns

  • Less complicated model

  • Influenced by tidytexts classification of positive/negative sentiment

  • Many more datapoints available

I will use analysis to determine which is best, but first I want to do some more data exploration.

  scale_fill_gradient(trans = "log")

I find the frequency of the word good and subtract the frequency of the word bad for each review. I then plot this against the star rating.

																											ggplot(data=no_freq_data, aes(x=factor(stars), y=log(positivewords-negativewords), fill=factor(stars))) +geom_boxplot()+theme_minimal()

Here, I am using no_freq_data.

I plot the frequency of positive subtract the number of negative words against the star rating.

It appears that there is some correlation in both cases. It is hard to see from the data exploration which set of explanatory variables will work best for our purposes.

Analytical Method

My plan is to initially fit a tree to both no_freq_data and freq_data in order to compare them both. Then, moving forward with the best dataset, I plan to use a random forest for my final model.

The reason for this choice is that ranger() is extremely efficient and will be able to cope with our large dataset. Since our data is categorical, and we dont expect a linear relationship between our explanatory and response variable, this seems like a good fit. We dont have to worry so much about overfitting since the errors are different for each tree and will hopefully average out across the forest.

Regression would be hard to apply to freq_data due to the sheer number of explanatory variables. Here, we have 2861 different columns in our dataframe. Working in high dimensional space like this would likely take a huge amount of time if we were to use regression. We certainly couldnt apply something like backwards variable selection since the model with every variable would be giant.

A linear model might be able to be used for no_freq_data. I think, however, a random forest would be better suited to the data, as well as faster and work better on a low RAM computer. It is hard to tell whether a linear model or a forest will do a better job in terms of mean squared error.

Initially, I will use rpart() on freq_data:

My intuition was correct in that user_review_count is a very strong indicator of star rating, as well as the frequency of the word good. Lots of the other variables that come up were all part of the word cloud we looked at earlier.

The above tree has a high complexity parameter so we can get an idea of the structure. However, I also wanted to apply a more complex tree:

																											#models using a more complicated tree
complex_tree = rpart(factor(stars)~., data = head(freq_data,9000), control=rpart.control(cp=0.00001, xval=10))
																										
																											conf_matr = table(predict(complex_tree, tail(freq_data[,-1],1000)) %>% apply(1,function(x){which.max(x)}), tail(freq_data,1000)$stars)

Lets see what happens if we apply the same model to no_freq_data this is the same data but without the frequencies of words. I will only take the first 10,000 lines so that the comparison is fair.

It doesnt seem much different than the model that included all the frequencies! This surprised me a lot since from the data exploration it seemed like including the word frequencies would be a good idea. It seems that, going forward, it would be much better to not include the word frequencies, seeing as it uses many many more explanatory variables (10 compared to 2861) and doesnt seem to improve the model much at all. I could save a lot of time and also potentially use an order of magnitude more rows.

Lets continue with the no_freq_data then!

I will apply a random forest. I will need to test different values of mtry - this is the number of variables to split into at each node. The default value is \(\lfloor\sqrt{P}\rfloor\) which is 3 - I will try some other values and see which works best. 

																											no_freq_data[is.na(no_freq_data)] <- 0
p = ncol(no_freq_data)-1
rows = nrow(no_freq_data)
mtry = c(1,2,3,4,5)
oob = c()

for (i in mtry){
nofreq_forest = ranger(factor(stars)~., data = head(no_freq_data,10000), mtry=i, verbose=FALSE, min.node.size = 1, num.trees=50, importance="permutation", classification = TRUE)
oob = c(oob, sum(diag(table(true=tail(no_freq_data$stars,10000), pred=predict(nofreq_forest, data=tail(no_freq_data,10000))$predictions)))/10000)
}

cbind(mtry, oob)

																											mtry = mtry[which.max(oob)]

It seems like mtry=2 is the best option, so Ill stick to that.

We have seen in class that we cannot overfit by using too many trees (num.trees) and so I will make this as large as I can run in a reasonable amount of time on my computer. Lets try 100 trees.

																											nofreq_forest = ranger(factor(stars)~., data = no_freq_data, mtry=mtry, verbose=FALSE, min.node.size = 1, num.trees=100, importance="permutation", classification = TRUE)

##              0.0785777854

It looks like the variable importance (under the permutation measure) for each of the explanatory variables is positive; they all give a decrease in the out of bag error compared to when that value is randomly shuffled.

Month and day have the lowest variable importance, which is totally unsurprising. What I do find interesting is that their importance is non-negative. I cant think of why this might be the case. Perhaps there is some sort of seasonal effect occurring. Or perhaps the variable importance is so close to zero that the positive permutation score is just due to randomness.

The variables with the highest importance are unsurprisingly the count of positive and negative words. This is what we expected from the data exploration stage. These are the only variables that take into account the actual text of the review itself. The number of negative words is apparently more important than the number of positive words. Perhaps a user who rates a business very low is more likely to use more strong language than a user who rates a business very high.

The number of votes a review received was the only other explanatory variable from the review data. This had lower variable importance than I expected, but it was still positive.

In terms of user data, the number of reviews a user received, the number of fans, the number of votes sent and the number of compliments received all got a relatively high permutation variable importance. Again, we saw in the data exploration that the number of reviews was positively correlated with stars so this is unsurprising. The other user data: the year they have been yelping since, the friend count and the elite status were relatively less important.

If we look at the confusion matrix:

We can see that there is a lot of confusion between 4 and 5. There is also a big confusion between 1 and 5 stars. I would guess that this is due to users with very little data about them and who didnt leave very long reviews. Due to 1 and 5 being the most popular category, the model puts them there.

The variable importance is very similar in this case, but the OOB prediction error is much lower at only 20.2%. It seems that, for a review that actually has a high star rating, the model is quite good at detecting such (it gets 90.62 % correct). However, for reviews that have a low rating, the model struggles more to place it (it only gets 58.41% correct).

Conclusion

We have created a model that predicts the star rating (from 1 to 5) that a yelp review is given by a user, given the data yelp keeps about said user, as well as the count of words in the review with a positive/negative sentiment. The model predicts the correct star rating correctly 54.73% of the time, and is correct to within one star 81.77% of the time. We have created a similar model which predicts whether a review gets higher or lower than 3.5 stars with an accuracy of 79.8%.

Discussion

Limitations

  • The main limitation is my processing power. I do not have access to computers with a high amount of RAM or disk space. This puts a limit on the complexity of the models I can implement. More importantly, it restricts the size of the dataset I can use.

  • The exploratory variables I have set up only record the number of times each word appears in the data. Although the package I am using accounts for variants of the same word (eg aches, ached, and ache all appear in the dataset), I cannot deal with phrases or combinations of words. For example, if one review says very good and another says not good, my data analysis would put them in the same category.

  • A limitation could be words that are not included in the package. For example, swear words are not included, which could be an indicator that a reviewer feels very strongly about a business. There also might be slang words that are left off. In order to combat this, wed have to use all the words used in the data, however, as processing power is already a limitation, this would be very hard for us.

  • Misspellings are another limitation that, unless we went through the data manually, it is near impossible for us to deal with. We will have to make the assumption that the number of misspellings are small enough to not make a difference.

Strengths

  • A strength is that we have a lot of data to work with. This means that the amount of data we have is not a limiting factor. If we were able to access a more powerful computer, our model would easily be flexible enough to be inputted more data.

  • We have access to other data that yelp keeps on its users. As well as just using analysis on the words of the review itself, our model can be made much stronger by using these other attributes. For example, as weve seen in the data exploration, the number of reviews a user has made is quite a good indicator of the number of stars they will give.

  • Another good thing is that we do not have to worry about missing data. Yelp keeps the same amount of information about all of its customers, so we do not need to worry about using missing data techniques in our model.

Appendix 3 - creating frequencies of words as exploratory variables

																											no_freq_data = freq_data = freq_data_2 = review_data_tidy %>%
    left_join(user_data_tidy, by="user_id") %>%
    select(-c("user_id", "text"))
col_names = colnames(freq_data)

#remove words with special characters
wordlist = get_sentiments("bing")
wordlist = dplyr::filter(wordlist, !grepl('\\*', word))

#creates new columns for each word in wordlist giving frequency of that word in the review text
for (i in wordlist$word){
  assign(i,c())
  for(j in freq_data$text){
    review_string = tolower(gsub('[[:punct:] ]+',' ',j)) #removes punctuation and makes lowercase
    word_to_find = paste("", i, "") #makes sure the word is on its own (not part of a bigger word)
    count = str_count(review_string, word_to_find) #counts instances
    assign(i, c(get(i), count))
  }
  freq_data_2 = cbind(freq_data_2, get(i))
  col_names = c(col_names, toString(i))
  rm(list=i)
}

#removes the columns with all zeros
colnames(freq_data_2) = col_names

#removes columns we don't want
freq_data = freq_data_2[, colSums(freq_data_2!=0)>0] %>%
  select(-c("text", "user_id", "review_id", "year", "month","day"))
